Citizens' rights group warns against travel to Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) has warned black people traveling to Missouri of the state’s discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group’s statement reads: “The NAACP travel note issued for the state of Missouri, valid until August 28, 2017, invites all African-American travelers, visitors, and Missorians to be particularly attentive and extremely careful when traveling throughout the state, given the suspicious race-based events that have recently taken place here and across the state.”
According to the NAACP, the group was urged to issue a travel alert by the recent Missouri Act, which makes it more difficult to win cases of discrimination, as well as the fact that the state's law enforcement agencies are unequally targeting minorities.
“People’s rights are being violated.
They are pulled to the edge of the road because of their skin color, they are beaten or killed," Rod Chapel, president of the Missouri branch of NAACP, told The Kansas City Star.
"We've never had such intense complaints before."
This is the first such warning issued by the organization on the state of the United States.
The group referred to events such as racist insults against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances at the beginning of this year after he ran out of gas while driving through the state and was arrested by Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
In addition, the note refers to a recent report by the Attorney General of Missouri, which shows that black drivers in the state are 75% more likely to be stopped than white drivers.
"The note is meant to make people aware and alert their families, friends and co-workers to what might happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
“People need to be prepared, whether it’s taking bail money or informing relatives that they’re going through the state.”
According to the latest data from the FBI’s Hate Crimes Reporting Program, 100 hate crimes were documented in Missouri in 2015, placing the state 16th in terms of the number of similar violations across the country.
The travel alert is also a response to Missouri’s new law that makes it harder for a company to sue for discrimination in its search for housing or work.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had previously issued travel notes for Texas and Arizona after those states passed immigration laws that forced local authorities to arrest people for immigration violations because, according to the ACLU, it increases racial profiling.
Travel alerts are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but more recently, interest groups have begun using this measure as a response to certain domestic laws and trends in the United States.
Hepatitis: what could anyone know about the different forms of this severe disease?
Hepatitis, or inflammation of the liver, can be caused by five different hepatitis viruses: A, B, C, D and E.
All these viruses cause acute inflammation of the liver tissue.
However, with a malignant course, chronic hepatitis B and C can develop into liver cirrhosis, i.e. liver crease and liver cancer.
Kuulo Kutsar, Epidemiology Adviser to the Health Board, says that the signs of acute hepatitis are the same for all types of liver inflammation - fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, gray stools, dark urine, muscle and joint pain, and yellowing of the skin and mucous membranes.
The last symptom of the disease also comes from the popular name of liver inflammation jaundice.
In children, hepatitis can pass without signs of disease.
Different types of inflammation of the liver can be determined only on the basis of data from a laboratory study.
Acute hepatitis can turn into chronic hepatitis and go on for decades without any signs of the disease, which means that a person may not know anything about his dangerous liver-damaging disease.
Hearing Kutsar highlights different forms of hepatitis and describes their course in more detail.
Hepatitis A viruses spread from a sick person and infect us by eating contaminated food or drinking water, having sex, stooling an infected person’s hands and hands to food, surfaces, objects, getting into the mouth, and consuming drugs.
The risk group for hepatitis A infection includes family members and caregivers of the affected person, people with chronic liver diseases, people having sex with the infected person, men having sex with men, drug addicts, travelers visiting countries with a high prevalence of hepatitis A.
Vaccination can be prevented by vaccination, in particular, vaccination is recommended for people who travel extensively and are at risk of hepatitis A.
In addition, it is important to meet daily hygiene requirements: wash or disinfect hands, wash all fruits and vegetables before eating.
Hepatitis B viruses are transmitted by exposure to the blood of a sick person, injection of drugs, tattoos, piercing, use of blood-contaminated household items (toothbrushes, shaving tools), donation of blood, sex with a person suspected of hepatitis B, and from a mother with hepatitis B to a foetus/newborn.
The risk group for hepatitis B infection includes injecting drug users, sexual partners of the infected person, men who have sex with men, newborns of the infected mother, family members and carers who are ill, healthcare, rescue workers and police officers who are in contact with blood and other body fluids, and travelers visiting countries with high levels of hepatitis B.
It is possible to vaccinate people to prevent hepatitis B; in particular, it is recommended to vaccinate people at risk, as well as people with chronic liver disease, HIV-infected, sexually transmitted diseases and diabetes.
Other preventive measures against hepatitis B include: abstaining from the use, tattooing and piercing of foreign means of hygiene and manicure, other sharps and needles, and the use of condoms in case of contagious sex or the prevention of sexual risk behaviour.
Vaccination against hepatitis B is part of the national immunisation programme in Estonia and is free of charge for children.
Hepatitis C viruses are transmitted by contact with the blood of a sick person, by injecting drugs, tattooing, piercing, using blood-contaminated household media, by donating blood, by having sex with a person suspected of hepatitis C, and by a mother/newborn with hepatitis C.
The risk group for hepatitis C infection includes injecting drug users, sexual partners of the infected person, men having sex with men, newborns of the infected mother, sick family members and carers, contact with blood and other body fluids by health care, rescue workers and police officers, persons infected with HIV, and travelers visiting countries with high levels of hepatitis C.
The preventive measure for hepatitis C is: abstaining from the use of foreign hygiene and manicure tools, other sharp tools and needles, tattooing and piercing, and the use of condoms in case of contagious sex.
There is no vaccine against hepatitis C.
Hepatitis D is caused by the hepatitis D virus, which multiplies in the presence of the hepatitis B virus.
Therefore, hepatitis D infection occurs with hepatitis B or as a superinfection in patients with chronic hepatitis B.
Hepatitis D viruses are transmitted by contact with blood and other body fluids, by needles and syringes contaminated with them, sexually, and rarely by the infected mother to the fetus.
The risk group for hepatitis D is chronic hepatitis B virus carriers and people who do not have immunity against hepatitis B.
An effective preventive measure is vaccination with a hepatitis B vaccine, which also protects a person from infection with the hepatitis D virus.
Hepatitis E viruses are transmitted via faecal-oral transmission via drinking water and food, including eating little heat-treated beef, fish and shellfish, donor blood, shared syringes and from the infected mother to the fetus.
Travellers can be infected with hepatitis E in countries with high levels of disease.
Preventive measures against hepatitis E are the fulfillment of hygiene requirements: wash or disinfect hands after going to the toilet, before cooking and eating, after caring for the sick person.
Wash fruits and vegetables before consumption, avoid eating little heat-treated beef, fish and seafood, drink only safe drinking water, and avoid using drugs.
