Blocking critics from Facebook Don’t Candidate for State Office if You Can’t Cope With Voters’ Criticism
The father of our country knew a lot about the unfavorable media coverage.
The Americans loved George Washington, but it didn’t take long for the newspapers to start babbling him out for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism, of course, irritated him.
But he did not force his critics to remain silent.
Because in 1783, Washington said that "freedom of speech may be taken away from us, and in silence and silence we may be led to slaughter like sheep."
It brings me to the governor of Maryland, Larry Hogan, who has to work hard to be more like Washington.
Hogan’s officials have blocked and deleted at least 450 people who posted their opinions on his official Facebook page.
At the beginning of the week, he was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU).
The governor’s officials stamped the lawsuit null and void, and the online comments were swamped with counter-reactions in the style of “Who cares?”
“It’s just Facebook,” many said.
But it does matter.
And it matters a lot when it comes to a man like Hogan.
This is an astonishingly popular Republican governor in an overwhelmingly democratic state.
His acceptance rate is the second best among the 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not an unthinking, reactive buzzhead.
He has ruled the state with a firm hand, and he has strictly adhered to his principles.
In addition, he has used Facebook as the main means of communicating with his constituents quite skillfully, for example, showing off his bald head lazily for the first time after chemotherapy.
Thus, the governor's page, which is an official public forum managed by taxpayer-dollar-paid staff, is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous to block visitors.
Hogan's spokeswoman, Amelia Chasse, defended the governor's behavior in an interview with The Washington Post, arguing that blocking comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it’s too easy to paint a picture of online trolls, spammers, or a hateful crowd.
The Post had a conversation with several real people that Hogan blocked.
And that's what they are, real people who communicate with their chosen leaders, teachers, business owners and pastors, not internet trolls.
They all said that their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and by no means obscene.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post, emphasizing Hogan’s Catholicism.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Raman from Bowie, Maryland, did not incite anger, but rather hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I am disappointed that he has not responded to hate crimes or other recent news," he wrote in the commentary section of The Post.
“I also don’t like the idea that when a lot of people comment on the same topic, someone immediately indifferently calls it a collective effort, rather than admitting that it’s a lot of concerned citizens.”
What the governor’s official called a “directed spam attack” would probably be called “public support.”
The Facebook era allows you to easily match messages by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It is much cleaner than in the past, when workers had to be sent out to do the same, to collect newspapers with critical editorials and burn them, or to arrest protesters and force them to remain silent.
But that’s exactly what’s happening right now, just digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticized for dismissing Facebook and other social media channels.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who have been blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first significant judgments on this subject was made last week in Virginia.
U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris ruled in Alexandria that the chairman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the first amendment to the Constitution by blocking a voter from his Facebook page.
In Kentucky, the ACLU also visited Governor Matt Bevin (R) after using Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
At the time of Washington, affordable postal costs had a similar effect to the Internet.
Between 1776 and 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and anonymous writers eroded his way of managing.
And even then, Washington had to face anonymous trolls.
People wrote letters to the newspapers under pseudonyms such as Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius, shattering Washington’s decisions.
According to historical documents collected as part of George Washington's online letter-collection project, his office was buried under petitions criticizing his views on friendship, trade and shipping agreements with Britain.
But he did not force them to remain silent.
Freedom of speech, dissent and debate are the foundations of our country.
Proper leadership means accepting it.
