However, these riches are a source of suffering for the Papuan people, as they require the suffocating presence of a powerful Indonesian army.
A 2005 study by The New York Times found that Freeport paid local military personnel and military units about <0x24>20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to <0x24>150,000 for one officer.
Papuan aspirations for greater autonomy threaten this golden geese and are mercilessly dealt with.
Human rights activists say more than 500,000 Papuas have been killed since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian army.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, the mass killings in Papuan highlands in the 1970s amounted to genocide.
Last year alone, more than 3,900 peaceful protesters were arrested by Indonesian police in the area.
The 2016 Birsbane Archdiocese’s “We Lose Everything” report contains testimonies of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture (according to another report, rape and electric shocks are particularly common) and brutal repression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to count the number of victims because of these incidents happening every week," said Andreas Harsono, a researcher at Human Rights Watch Indonesia.
The screws are even tighter because Papuan natural resources have caused the influx of new settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
83% of the province’s 3.5 million inhabitants are Christian, but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the large Indonesian islands of Java, Kalimantan, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javan family canteens sell gado-gado with crispy chicken and mixed vegetables, served with peanut sauce.
