"Indigenous Papuan Mama-Mama's [women] will therefore lose their market share."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, known to the public as Jokowi, pledged in his 2014 election campaign to address these inequalities and human rights violations in Papua.
The former carpenter defeated 27 of the 29 constituencies of Papua, including Pania, on his way to the Jakarta presidential palace.
But very little has changed in Papua and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014, we voted for Jokow in the expectation that he will fulfill our hopes for the restoration of justice," You said.
In fact, only two months after Jokow took office in October, Paniai struggled in a low state.
On December 7, 2014, 11 children in Enarotal sang Christmas songs by the fire when two Indonesian soldiers appeared on a motorcycle from darkness.
The shocked children told them to turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone of voice and later returned with four soldiers.
Victims and witnesses said drunk soldiers chased children and beat them with their gun handles.
Then one of the soldiers shot at the children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was so brutally beaten that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby electoral commission building was set on fire, and the next day things escalated.
About 1,000 young men, women and children from Papua gathered for justice on the football field in front of the local police station and military command centre.
They wore ceremonial hunting vibes and performed the Papuan honey pago tribe’s waita dance, during which they ran around and imitated bird songs.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police and the military.
"If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them," according to an official document seen in TIME magazine, but not issued to local media outlets.
Yeremias Kayame (56), elder of the district of Kego Koto in Enarotal, sensed the threat and called for peace to be maintained, asking the crowd to go home.
No one wanted to listen.
"When I turned around, I was suddenly shot in the left wrist," he told TIME magazine in his bright colors on the veranda of the tree house.
Kayame still doesn't know who the shooter was, but he says the bullet came from the troops.
"There were many people, there were many shots," he adds.
A local man named Alfius Youw was shot three times, according to a cousin who saw him shot.
"I ran to him and searched his body to make sure it was him," Yohanes, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name, told Time magazine.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
Papuan Police Inspector General Yotje Mende told reporters that his subordinates only guaranteed the safety of his station as it was attacked.
“We need to protect ourselves if we are threatened with death,” Papuan police spokesman Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many injured.
News of the killings came to Jakarta the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura, in which he expressed his condolences to the families of the victims and promised to deal with the abuses in Papua.
"I want to solve this case now so it never happens again in the future," he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Wiranto said that he would establish an out-of-court mechanism to resolve the crimes against human rights committed.
Almost immediately came the apologies.
“Most of the crimes happened a long time ago.
Some of them occurred in the 1990s and early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to solving these crimes, but we must follow certain processes," he said.
Speaking to TIME magazine in Jakarta on June 5, Wiranto withdrew his words, saying he had no intention of setting up a complaint mechanism in Papua.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be settled by the law.”
Wiranto, who has been accused by the United Nations of crimes against human rights in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people in East Timor during the bloody 1999 independence referendum, said that 11 crimes against human rights have already been solved in Papua, including those in Pania.
The families of Paniai’s victims accepted such claims with gloomy mistrust.
"I've been interrogated four times in the last three years, but no progress has been made," Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
He says he still lives in fear years later.
"I'm afraid," he says.
"I'm afraid the military will arrest me, I'm afraid they'll shoot me."
His brother, Yacobus, confirmed the opinion that the people of Paniai were afraid to frame the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four victims.
"After the bodies were buried, the army came looking for me," he said.
The shooting hasn't stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot down villagers in the neighbouring Paniai Regiment in Deiyai.
One person was killed and 17 wounded, including children, as a result of a quarrel between villagers and the head of the construction company, who refused to transport the unconscious man to the hospital.
This man, 24, Ravianus Douw, who drowned in a nearby river while fishing, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company’s office at the construction site.
Police said the villagers threw stones at police officers, and the latter responded with warning shots.
But locals say a mobile brigade (Indonesian military police) started shooting at the people, killing one person.
"We were in a panic, afraid of revenge," said Dominggu Badi, 29, who lives near the hospital and saw the injured being recorded.
"I've been hiding in my house for two days."
The Deiyai parliament has called for the prosecution of the police officers involved and for the withdrawal of the police mobile brigade from the area.
Pania has always been a problem for the Indonesian government.
The lack of thoughtful development fuels the discontent of the honey, moni, dani, and damal tribes living in Papua’s mediocre highlands.
Many of them have joined the rebel army of the Free Papuan Movement (VPL), which claims to defend Papuan rights by carrying out incidental attacks and kidnappings among Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the leaders of the VPL are from Pania, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
In response, under the pretext of "protecting the sovereignty of the state", the military has arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of people in Paniai in recent years.
Some of them will never show up again.
Among Papuan people, Panias is known as a "tragic forgotten place".
Poverty fuels dissatisfaction.
The small amount of rice sold in Enarotal is too expensive for the locals to buy.
Bread is just as inaccessible.
People grow all their food on their own mainly sweet potatoes, in addition to a little fruit and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the work of women, each of whom can care for four or five sweet potato fields.
They usually keep most of the harvest for the family, the rest are sold on the local market.
Ten sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequalities have deepened between indigenous Papuan people and new migrants, many of whom have arrived since the opening of new routes at Nabire Airport.
The few jobs that exist will go to better educated and more prosperous migrants.
Papuans themselves often lack the capital or skills necessary to run a competitive business.
"Young people aren't interested in staying here because there's no jobs or money," said John Gobai, chairman of the Panai Tribal Council.
Separation keeps the eyes of the world away from Papua.
In addition, there are strict restrictions on external media.
By the beginning of this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Bastille Longchamp were expelled from Papua because "they did not follow relevant practices," although they had been given a rare filming license.
Phelim Kine, deputy head of Human Rights Watch’s Asia department, said Jokow’s election pledges to lift restrictions on reporting to promote transparency and development had not been implemented.
"Journalists attempting to report on the most turbulent eastern provinces of Papua and Western Papua in Indonesia face new threats of visa rejection and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
The lack of a persuasive look on the press means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely confined to the immediate neighbours of Papua.
In March, six Pacific nations, Tonga, Nauru, Belau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands, urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "a wide range of crimes" in Papua, including the Panai shooting.
These countries have also historically supported the VPL.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Arrmanatha Nasir dismissed the group’s allegations, telling reporters in Jakarta: “There is still democratic order and freedom of the press in Indonesia, so it would be difficult to bury evidence of cases of human rights violations.”
The local people want more foreign governments to be noticed.
When the Dutch official delegation headed by the country's human rights envoy, Kees Van Bar, visited Jayapura on May 4, local people interrupted their silence, according to a source who was present at the meeting but wanted to remain anonymous, urging: "We want freedom."
Indonesia will hold new presidential elections in 2019, but the Papuan people do not believe they will vote for Jokow again.
"Jokowi is a man of good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the shooting of Paniai," said Hobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokow to be told that, in addition to the constant threat of a predatory army, the people of Pania are suffering from misery because of poor educational and health services.
According to Gobai, the people of Paniai, like other Papuan people, regard the vote given to Jokow as a debt he has to pay.
"They don't need money, they want justice," he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of Paniaia's shooting victims managed to make one last symbolic revolt by burying the body of one of the victims on the ground opposite the police station and military base.
Knowing that justice may never be established, they will at least not allow those responsible to forget their crimes.
"One of our family members was killed," says Yacobus with his head lowered.
"What else can we do?"
