From which parts of the world are we moving to Estonia?
Last year, the Police and Border Guard Board (PPA) extended and issued a record number of more than 13,000 residence permits to third-country nationals who have mostly travelled to Estonia for work, study or family.
When, for example, it was decided to issue a temporary residence permit to 6,702 foreigners last year, the figure was 4,928.
The authorities cannot say how many immigrants will eventually remain in Estonia permanently, but such an analysis is being prepared by the Ministry of the Interior.
Ten years ago, nearly 500 Ukrainians moved to Estonia every year, but in recent years this number is approaching 2,000.
The number of applicants for residence permits increased dramatically during the Ukrainian crisis - in 2014, 1,087 people received a temporary residence permit, a year earlier, 675.
According to Statistics Estonia, the number of Ukrainian citizens is growing the most in Estonia – last year 850 Ukrainian citizens arrived in Estonia more than left.
“The Ukrainian community has always been large in Estonia, and due to the difficult circumstances in the country, it is natural for people to look for work and study opportunities in a country where the community and many families are already ahead of them,” said Kristin Rammus, spokeswoman for the Ministry of the Interior.
Last year and since then, the number of Ukrainians who have been granted temporary residence permits was even higher than the number of Russian citizens, although in a total of ten years, the most temporary residence permits have been issued to the latter.
While Ukrainians come here to work, Russian citizens come here mainly for family migration.
"Given the historical Russian community here, they are also more likely to have the biggest family ties with people living in Russia," said Helina Maasing, a migration researcher at the Academy of Homeland Security.
"If you look at where Russian citizens who have received Estonian residence permits have moved to live, then Ida-Virumaa is immediately behind Harjumaa," he added, pointing out that about 40 per cent of them have married a citizen of the European Union.
Last year, 1,696 Russian citizens were granted temporary residence permits, which is also a record number.
At the same time, the number of Russians wishing to extend their residence permits decreased.
"The reason for this is that instead of extending the residence permit, a new residence permit has been applied for permanent residence in Estonia," Rammus, a spokesperson for the Ministry of the Interior, said, adding that Russian citizens' interest in the Estonian residence permit has remained rather stable for years.
Foreigners who have lived here for at least three years can apply for a new residence permit for permanent residence in Estonia from the previous year.
Its purpose is to facilitate the stay of adapted people.
A residence permit for a long-term resident, for example, requires five years.
Because of the new residence permit, the extension of the old residence permit has also decreased.
For example, last year, 146 Ukrainians who have worked here for at least three years were granted such a residence permit.
Now the Ukrainians can change jobs, and the Estonian state will no longer make a fuss about whether the wage criterion has been met.
This residence permit became hugely popular - applicants last year were still holders of gray passports (1029), Russians (487), Indians (54) and Nigerians (36).
A total of 1968 people received a residence permit to settle in Estonia, among them 23 Americans, 12 Egyptians, 18 Georgians and the same number of Chinese.
In the first half of this year, the total number of such applicants is already 1269.
In ten years, Nigeria has surprisingly become one of the most active applicants for Estonian residence permits.
While three residence permits were issued to Nigerians in 2007, 200 were issued last year.
They come from Nigeria to study at these universities.
Estonian higher education institutions are also popular among Georgians, Chinese and Turks, for example.
The number of Indian, Bangladeshi and Nigerian citizens has risen largely due to educational migration.
The rule also applies to them, that where a community has formed in advance, it is easier for others to come there," Rammus added.
Over the past ten years, two people have also moved to Estonia, for example, from North Korea, as well as from Laos and Madagascar.
Ten people have come from Cuba, 231 from South Korea, 40 from Indonesia and four from Uruguay.
