New results of age assessment tests for Swedish asylum seekers published
The latest results of the test show that more than 80 percent of the people tested were older than 18, but not everyone believes in the accuracy of the results.
The Swedish National Institute of Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) started testing early this year.
The tests were created to further assess the age during the asylum application process after criticisms were made against the Swedish Migrations Verket for failing to correctly determine the age of a number of allegedly minor refugees.
So far, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Institute of Forensic Medicine has released a total of 2,481 test results between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were rated 18 years or older, and in another 25 cases, the Forensic Institute estimated that the test subject “may be 18 years or older.”
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the person is "presumably younger than 18".
Tests are only used when the age of a person is in question.
According to Johan Göransson, who works at the Institute of Forensic Medicine, the results are consistent with those of the previous months.
“We don’t see a big difference from previous months’ statistics, the numbers are pretty consistent,” he told The Local.
The fact that a large proportion of the cases were rated older than 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers have lied about their age.
In May, the Institute released the results of 581 tests and said that in 442 cases "there are indications that the person being studied is 18 years or older."
But when the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet looked at the results of these 581 tests, it turned out that in 243 cases the person had directly claimed to be 18 this year.
This medical age-assessment method, in which X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI of knee joints are taken and then analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has been criticized in some circles.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institutet, whose duties include assessing the biological maturity of humans to determine whether they passed puberty earlier or later than usual.
“I’ve had reason to think about it, and I don’t think the measurement method we’re using now should be used.
Determining the biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can’t say for sure, we shouldn’t pretend we can,” he told the Metro newspaper.
But Johan Göransson of the Institute of Forensic Medicine defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, it can be said that the risk of imprecisely categorizing a child into adulthood is low.
The highest risk, perhaps 10%, is when a person is just under 18.”
