The electric car revolution will significantly change the demand for metals.
Who are the winners and losers?
Not only will the electric car revolution change everything from the fuel market to infrastructure, it will also create new winners and losers in the metal market.
While mining giants like Glencore can say that they will win in one place and lose in the other, smaller mining companies will not be helped.
Today, Glencore earns from coal and oil, but in the future, in the era of electric cars, the demand for cobalt, lithium, copper, aluminum and nickel will grow.
This year, the British, French and Norwegian governments have decided to ban the sale of new cars using fossil fuels in the coming decades.
That’s why Volvo has already announced that they are planning to abandon the internal combustion engine, and Tesla is launching a cheaper Model 3 electric car.
According to Bloomberg New Energy Finance, more electric cars have been sold in the last two decades than cars that use oil-produced fuels.
"For some metals, it changes everything," said Simona Gambranini, a raw material analyst at Capital Economics, to Bloomberg.
We have already seen a major impact on such metals as cobalt and lithium, the demand for which has been increasing for years.
Electric cars have about three times more copper than conventional cars, Glencore said.
More copper is needed at charging stations, which is why Exane BNP Paribas estimates it will increase copper demand by about 5% by 2025.
The increase in demand for electric car batteries means additional demand for lithium, cobalt, graphite and manganese.
Glencore is profiting from the rising trend in electric cars from rising copper prices and being the world’s largest cobalt producer, the Jefferies Group predicted.
According to this brokerage firm, the other winners of the electric car race are Freeport-McMoRan and First Quantum Minerals.
The market is already responding to a changing trend.
This year, the Cobalt has increased by 70 percent on the London Metal Exchange.
The price increase last year was 37%.
Copper has also increased by 14% this year, mainly due to economic growth.
Glencore’s stock rose 20 percent in London, after surpassing rivals Rio Tinto Group, BHP Billito and Anglo American.
On the losing side are lead companies like Recyclex and Campine, who have to adapt to the new era.
The main end-use of lead is batteries supplying power to car starters with petrol and diesel engines.
Electric cars use lithium-ion batteries.
"This is a serious risk to lead demand unless other uses are found to overcome the drop in demand," Michael Widmer, Metal Market Analyst at Bank of America Merrill Lynch, said in a statement.
The effects of the unfolding trend have not yet been noticed in the form of lead price movements.
Lead has risen 17 percent this year, making it the best metal in London among the major industrial metals to rise in price.
Investors will only see problems with metal in the distant future.
"I'm not sure it's that bad for lead, because cheap oil keeps conventional cars competitive," said Herwig Schmidt, sales manager at Triland Metals.
When the demand for lead drops, it happens slowly.
This could happen in about 10 years.
In the meantime, stricter emission standards mean that the demand for hybrid cars, which depend on advanced lead-based batteries for frequent engine start-ups, is growing, according to the international research organisation for lead and zinc.
Light metals such as aluminium replace steel, as a lighter car can drive farther with less electricity.
This explains the additional demand for aluminium of 1.6 million tonnes already between 2013 and 2016.
It accounts for 2.7 percent of the world’s aluminium production.
This trend is likely to worsen, Widmer said.
Aluminium has increased by 13% this year, as the growing demand from car manufacturers has led to a market deficit.
Steel producers don't sleep.
AK Steel Holding is partnering with General Motors to use nanotechnology to produce lightweight car bodies.
ArcelorMittal and Tata Steel Europe are also trying to develop a lighter alloy steel to resist aluminum.
"Transient steel should be the answer to this development," said Sylvain Brunet, an analyst at Exane BNP Paribas.
We see some progress in Europe.
The end of the oil age can also bring suffering to the platinum.
Last year, about half of this precious metal was spent on diesel-powered car catalysts, metal refiner Johnson Matthey said.
"Many of the raw materials in high demand today, such as oil and platinum, may not be in high demand in the future," said Bernard Dahdah, a raw material analyst at Natixis.
This does not mean that raw materials as a whole will become less important, but their importance will change within 15 years.
Platinum manufacturers expect continued demand for diesel-hybrid cars.
Uncore CEO Marc Grynberg said that by 2025, more hybrid cars will be sold than full-electric cars.
A great hope for platinum manufacturers over the next 10 years is that Toyota Motor and Hyundai Motos will develop hydrogen cell-based cars that depend on platinum to produce hydrogen electricity.
However, this technology has not yet proven itself commercially.
"Diesel seems to be a clear loser on the road to electric cars," Brunet of Exane BNP Paribas said.
German car manufacturers were hit hard in July after a Stuttgart court banned the use of diesel in the hometowns of Mercedes-Benz and Porsche.
