Clubs are allowed to spend a lot of money to recruit players, but they have to balance this with legal sources of income that allow them to get out of the football business.
The FFP was founded by Michel Platini after he was elected president of UEFA in 2007.
This former French player believed that clubs that fell into high debt in search of success actually engaged in fraud and risked ruin if banks or owners were to give up support.
Since 2011, the FFP has focused on monitoring the losses of clubs instead of their debts.
This change means that the business model that Roman Abramovich first used at Chelsea in 2003 – to buy a club with potential and then make a big expense to improve the team and create a global brand – is more difficult to implement.
During the current three-year assessment period of FFP, which will run until 2018, clubs may suffer losses of up to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million.
