Neymar concluded a five-year contract, which makes it possible to show the transitional fee over the next five years as an amount of EUR 44,4 million over the year.
For the first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014, the PSG, along with Manchester City from Abu Dhabi, received the most severe penalties.
PSG was fined <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>60 million (at the moment <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>82 million), which was later reduced to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>20 million, and the club was required to limit the Champions League team to 21 players instead of the usual 25.
UEFA is looking for clubs that may try to outsmart regulatory financial institutions by blowing up their income through companies affiliated with club owners.
The Qatari company may sponsor PSG, but if the value of the sponsorship is considered to exceed the standard market rates, UEFA would not allow it to be counted as official income.
This was the case in 2014, when UEFA decided that the value of the support from the Qatar Tourism Authority for PSG was bloated.
It has been said that a certain part of Neymar’s PSG service could come from Qatar through payments made by the 2022 World Cup Management Committee.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 deny that Neymar could become an ambassador to the World Cup, and argue that UEFA regulators could easily expose such a maneuver.
Penalties previously imposed on PSG mean that UEFA is even more vigilant in any attempt to disregard the rules.
