Bank of England keeps interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to report that interest rates will remain at their previous levels, as weak economic growth and the easing of inflation have softened speculation about the rise.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will remain sluggish, as households’ stalled incomes have put interest rates on hold.
The policymakers of the Bank’s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted to keep the 6:2 rates at 0.25%, and fewer members are calling for an increase this month as slow growth has weakened support for growth.
In its quarterly inflation report, the bank cut its growth forecast for 2017 to 1.7% and for 2018 to 1.6%, warning that pressure on household incomes will remain, as inflation is still expected to rise to close to 3% in autumn.
At the same time, the bank also signalled that the increase in rates will be necessary to curb inflation caused by Brexit over the next few years, and a higher-than-expected rise in credit costs may be necessary in the financial markets.
Members also voted to partially withdraw the mammoth package that was launched a year ago as a result of Brexit.
