In the minutes of the decision on the rate, the Bank states: "In the medium-term forecast of the MPC, gross domestic product (GDP) will remain powerless in the near future, as the difficult situation of households' real incomes will continue to have an impact on consumption."
With regard to rates, it was reiterated that a "slight tightening of monetary policy" is needed to alleviate inflation, and this at a "slightly higher" rate than the markets have expected.
The stock market is currently forecasting a first increase in the third quarter of next year and a second increase in 2020.
However, the bank emphasized that all jumps are gradual and limited.
The Bank’s reduced growth forecasts for this year and next year are comparable to the May forecasts of 1.9% and 1.7%.
The forecast for 2018 of 1.8 percent growth remained stable.
After this news, the pound dropped against the dollar and the euro.
The pound dropped 0.5% to USD 1.31 and 0.4% to EUR 1.11.
The decision not to make any changes is due to recent disappointing growth figures, which have dampened the growing hopes of rising GDP in the second quarter from 0.2% in the previous three months to 0.3%.
The bank says that growth is likely to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will pick up slightly at the end of the year.
The Bank’s latest inflation report gave little reason to cheer households suffering from rising inflation and unfortunate wage increases, saying that the situation would get a little worse before it improved.
It was added that monetary policy cannot prevent a shock to incomes in the next few years, but wages are expected to recover noticeably towards the end of the three-year forecast.
Due to the weak pound, the economy is also stimulated by a growing demand for British production, which partly compensates for lower consumer costs.
The decision comes a year after the rates were moved to 0.25% last August after a shocking EU referendum that caused the pound to suddenly weaken.
The bank estimates that it will likely take four years to fully inflate prices and the economy.
Prior to the Bank’s last decision, there was a growing demand for an increase in the rate, as inflation had increased the pressure on tightly-knit households; in July, three policymakers called for a 0.5% increase in the rate.
