The NHS is prescribing a controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people.
As of September, patients will have access to “transformative” HIV preventative treatment after a battle in the Supreme Court over whether the NHS should fund the drug.
The NHS England reported that the National Health Service is now making pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) available to an estimated 10,000 people during the initial three-year clinical trial, a tablet administered before intercourse that has shown a reduction of about 86% in the risk of infection in high-risk individuals.
The NHS agreed to fund the clinical trial after the Appellate Court backed last year’s ruling that the NHS would be able to pay for PrEP, despite the NHS’s own claims that the drug should be funded by local governments instead.
NHS England CEO Simon Stevens welcomed this move, which was announced Thursday, as a “new large-scale intervention,” while the National Aid Fund (NAT) described it as “a pivotal moment.”
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start enrolling people. More clinics will be added in October before the program is deployed everywhere in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of HIV drugs taken before intercourse to reduce the risk of contracting HIV.
The results of clinical trials indicate that PrEP significantly reduces the transmission of HIV among people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sexual intercourse means that there is a sufficient amount of certain drugs in the human body that prevent infection with HIV.
Such drugs can be taken daily or no later than two hours before intercourse.
Candidates eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transgender people and people whose partners are infected with HIV and do not receive treatment.
Clinicians identify suitable individuals who are willing to participate in the clinical trial, including men, women, transgender people and those whose HIV partner is not receiving antiretroviral therapy.
People who live in England and have chosen a family doctor there can also register at a local sexual health clinic participating in the program.
The program costs <0xC2><0xA3>10 million, and NHS England signed a contract to receive the drugs this week after an international tender.
The aim of the clinical trial is to assess the real potential of PrEP by gathering clinical evidence about who the drug is intended for and how it is consumed and applied in the big picture.
Stevens said: “This new large-scale intervention should complement and amplify the broad and increasingly successful fight against HIV transmission.
This is yet another milestone in more than three decades of combating one of humanity’s greatest health problems.”
Deborah Gold, CEO of NAT, said: “This is a pivotal moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if properly targeted at those who need it and are at risk, offers an opportunity to change the HIV epidemic in England.
Since September, people at high risk of HIV in England have access to a powerful new tool that is individually manageable and not dependent on negotiations with a partner, thereby improving many lives through this NHS-funded clinical trial.
We warmly welcome this announcement.”
Ian Green, CEO of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: “It is now essential to ensure that the clinical trial across the country is pushed quickly and that no person at risk of HIV is left out.
Now that the clinical trial drug for PrEP has been procured, we are on our way to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of contracting HIV.
Public Health shadow minister Sharon Hodgson said: “The start of the PrEP clinical trial is very welcome and much delayed after months of delays and dragging the government’s feet.
Evidence shows how much this medicine can change to prevent HIV and stop the spread of this life-changing infection.
This clinical trial takes us one step closer to a full understanding of the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the clinical trial be implemented across the country as soon as possible to protect people who are exposed to HIV and to bring us one step closer to stopping the spread of HIV in society."
