Trump's new chief of staff plans to cut the president's media consumption.
Others have tried and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it.
In that case, he would be the first.
Politico writes that the new White House chief of staff plans to curb the flow of information reaching President Trump, including news, in the hope that it will keep the boss in smoother water.
Here's an excerpt from reporter Josh Dawsey:
"When the new White House chief of staff, John F. Kelly, met with senior officials on his first working day, he pointed out a key problem President Donald Trump had in the White House, which he planned to solve by getting bad information into the hands of the president.
Kelly told officials that information must flow through him, either on paper or at meetings, because the president would make better decisions if he was given good information.”
Kelly’s diagnosis seems entirely logical, but others have also tried, and they have failed to tame Trump by monitoring his media consumption.
President Trump’s relationship with television goes back decades, and now that he’s in the White House, his television habits haven’t disappeared.
"When Trump was angry about the unfair media coverage, it was worth showing him that he was also being honestly reported in the affected publications," former campaign adviser Sam Nunberg told Politico in February.
Politico Tara Palmeri wrote at the time that “six former campaigners said that the key to managing Trump’s Twitter habits is to ensure that his personal media consumption consistently includes praise.”
All right, all right.
But the idea that Trump’s Twitter habits have once been “controlled” is ridiculous.
Perhaps these campaigners know something the rest of us don’t know that Trump’s tweets would have been even more incendiary without their intervention.
We’ll probably never know about the tweets Trump didn’t post.
When his helpers were able to save him from trouble even a few times, their efforts were worth it.
But no one has been able to stop Trump from consistently causing controversy.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, which is made up of competing clicks, people are exclusively trying to promote their own interests by providing Trump with material that supports their worldview, but may not always be reliable.
In May, Politico wrote about the inclination of the advisers to feed the president with information of questionable strategic value.
One of the examples described by reporter Shane Goldmacher is as follows:
“Current and former Trump subordinates say that Trump may react to negative press, particularly information leaks with damaging effects, explosively, obsessing about identifying their source.
This was the case at the end of February, when someone gave the president a photocopy of an article on the GotNews.com website belonging to internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson that accused deputy chief of staff Katie Walsh of being a "source of multiple information leaks" from the White House.
It doesn’t matter that Johnson has been permanently blocked from Twitter because of the mockery, or that he didn’t provide any specific evidence, or that he has also filed false accusations in the past and withdrew them.
Trump read the article and started asking his subordinates about Walsh.”
Goldmacher added that then chief of staff Reince Priebus and White House chief of staff Rob Porter “have tried to establish a system for managing and documenting documents reaching Trump.”
How did it work?
Kelly tries to do exactly the same thing three months later.
He may prove to be a more effective leader than Priebus, but Trump is still impulsive and his assistants are still competing for influence.
These unchanging factors make Kelly's mission very difficult.
