Eesti Pank purchased bonds worth EUR 149 million in July as part of the euro area central banks’ public sector asset purchase programme, and the central bank’s bond portfolio grew to EUR 4.36 billion.
The central bank does not publish any more detailed information on purchases.
The President of the Bank of Estonia, Hardo Hansson, has previously explained, in response to an interpellation by members of the Riigikogu, that the Eurosystem central banks’ asset purchase programme includes three different purchase programmes: financial sector covered bonds, asset-backed bonds (ABS) and public sector bonds (PSPP).
The central bank buys bonds from the market to encourage investors who have sold the bonds to invest their money elsewhere.
The effect of purchases is to reduce the return on lower-risk assets and to motivate investors to take higher risks.
As a general rule, each central bank purchases government bonds under a public sector bond purchase programme, while bonds from other countries are not purchased.
As the state of Estonia has not issued bonds, Eesti Pank will make so-called replacement purchases within the allocated volume.
The central banks also purchase substitution bonds in countries where the supply of bonds complying with the purchase programme is limited.
According to Hansson, Eesti Pank generally purchases bonds from European institutions, such as those of the European Financial Stability Facility and the European Investment Bank.
Eesti Pank will purchase bonds under the asset purchase programme as of March 2015.
In the meantime, Elering bonds were also acquired, but from June 2016 Eesti Pank will no longer purchase Elering bonds.
The Bank of Finland will purchase Elering and Eesti Energia bonds on behalf of the central banks of the euro area from June.
