Dinosaur used protective color to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a shape, albeit quite frightening.
Scientists have now revealed the first findings of an incredible rhino-sized creature discovered by a Canadian miner, so well preserved that experts have described it as the "Mona Lisa of the Dinosaurs."
It is so well preserved that it was even possible to identify that its scaled skin was reddish-brown in color and its past had been somewhat "complex".
A report published in Current Biology described the creature as “the best-preserved armored dinosaur ever found” and “one of the best dinosaurs in the world.”
The fossil is a new species of nodosaur that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous, 110-112 million years ago.
Its incredibly good preservation struck scientists who describe it as “really remarkable.”
This scaled-up vegetarian is the best-preserved type of fossil ever found, according to National Geographic magazine.
It was discovered on March 21, 2011 by Shawn Funk when he dug a Suncor Millenium mine near Fort McMurray, North Alberta, Canada.
He struck something that did not resemble the surrounding rock, and decided to investigate more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
For the next six years, efforts were made to excavate the animal from a 2,500-pound (1,100-pound) plot of land.
After all this hard work, the final result is now ready to be brought to the public's attention.
"If you pee a little, you can almost believe he's asleep," said lead author Caleb Brown, a researcher at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature is exhibited.
"It goes into scientific history as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs."
While examining his skin, researchers found that this herbivore, though covered in scales and resembling a walking tank, was likely to be significantly threatened by meat-eating dinosaurs.
This large scaled dinosaur used red and white to hide from predators, and used a shading technique known as counter-shading, which is also used by many modern animals.
This, according to experts, allowed the dinosaur to better blend into the surroundings and avoid enemies, as the larger dinosaurs were likely to hunt him.
This 110 million-year-old creature from the Nodosaur family first appeared in the news in May and is now a visitor to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Scientists have now studied the creature and named it after Mark Mitchell, a labyrinth at the Borealopelta Markmitchelli Museum, who was part of a team that spent more than 7,000 hours exposing the animal.
Thanks to the amazing preservation of the specimen, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the shape and size of the scales on the animal's body.
They discovered a counter-eclipse, a method of protection common in the animal kingdom, which means that the upper half of the creature was darker than the lower half.
Although counter-eclipse is common, the findings come as a surprise, as Borealopelta is much larger than the animals that live today.
This suggests that the dinosaur was actively hunted by other carnivorous dinosaurs, that evolution preferred shading as a survival tactic over confrontation.
But most of the animals that today use counter-shadowing — such as deer, zebras, or armadillos — are much smaller and more vulnerable to prey, suggesting that nodosaurs had to really work hard to survive.
"The intense hunting of the hugely large and plentiful scaled dinosaur shows how dangerous the Cretaceous dinosaur predators could have been," Brown said.
A chemical analysis of the organic compounds in the scales also revealed that the skin of the dinosaur was reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal to get clues about its life, including the contents of its intestines, to find out what the animal ate for its last meal.
They believe that the dinosaur fell in the river when it died, reaching the sea with a stream, where it sank in front of its back to the ocean floor.
At the time, Alberta was as warm as it is now in southern Florida, and rivers and oceans probably stretched far beyond the hinterland than they are now.
"This nodosaurus is truly remarkable because it is completely covered with preserved scalloped skin, while it has also remained three-dimensional, preserving the original shape of the animal," Brown said.
"As a result, the animal today looks almost the same as it did in the Cretaceous period.
You don’t have to use a lot of imagination to reconstruct it – it’s enough just to squint your eyes and it feels like it’s asleep.”
The Cretaceous era was a time when huge two-legged carnivorous dinosaurs - the theropods - roamed the earth.
Although their king Tyrannosaurus rex lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, this armored dinosaur may have been hunted by some of his formidable predecessors.
These include the Acrocanthosaurus, a 38-foot (11.5-meter) tall monster weighing six tons.
Scientists, whose recent findings have been published in the journal Current Biology, believe that Borealopelta was washed into the sea after death and mummified in the mud.
The creature was discovered on March 21, 2011 by Shawn Funk when he dug up a Millenium mine near Fort McMurray, North Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including skin and armor, and it is comprehensive from cone to hips.
These creatures were on average 18 feet (five meters) long and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1300 kg).
Two 20-inch squirrels came out of its shoulders.
Scientists believe that this scaled herbivore was adventurous through present-day Western Canada until a flooded river washed up in its high seas.
However, the dinosaur’s submarine burial site helped preserve its scales in exquisite detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of the skin are still covered along the armoured plates along the dinosaur skulls.
As Michael Greshko wrote in National Geographic magazine: "This degree of preservation is as rare as winning the lottery.
The more I look at it, the more incredible it looks.
The hardened skin remains still cover the lumpy shell plates on the animal's skull.
His right foreleg lies beside him, and five toes are stretched upwards.
I can count the scales on his feet."
How did one activist find the answer to the question "Whose streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shocked.
Just the day after traveling to New York City, this resident of St. Louis sat in a rented room through Airbnb, browsing Facebook on his phone.
He got into a post from his former schoolmate.
It said, "Police just killed an 18-year-old boy, and he's still on the street."
He was confused why no one else had posted this information in his stream, which is why he shut down Facebook and opened Twitter.
The <0x40>TheePharoah user's posts had been shared repeatedly on his timeline.
A rapper from the St. Louis area broadcasted a real-time tweet about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black man who was killed by a white policeman in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body lying on the street, staying there for four hours.
"That's crazy," Ferrell thought to himself.
But death was nothing new for him or his community.
She put her phone down, but later that night saw another tweet announcing this time a gathering of people on Canfield Drive.
They shared photos of a police tape and screaming people, and a man claiming to be Brown’s father, holding a sign that said, “Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!”
He watched a live stream where a policeman stood in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another police officer whispered a rifle and shouted, "I'll kill you all... animals."
Ferrell remembers how he hit himself with the thought, "It's unusual."
"It's not the kind of murder we're used to, which we might call typical."
I felt fear at that moment.
I was angry and crying.”
He booked a return flight and drove home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., he went to his father to pick up his six-year-old daughter and decided that the next morning they would travel alone to Ferguson.
What happened with Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is a central theme in the new documentary Whose Streets?, which will premiere in theaters on August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, love and loss, strength and tenacity from the point of view of the people who live in this community and who filled the streets demanding answers.
When Ferrell and his daughter, who was wearing a floral dress and a matching crown on her head, approached Ferguson, they again discussed the experiences and living conditions of the blacks, which had been discussed many times before that morning.
“Do you remember when I taught you how the black community had to fight for their rights?” she recalls, asking herself.
"We're driving to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that's not right."
"I couldn't take him with me," Ferrell said later.
“What is happening now is the culmination of what has happened in the past.
He needs to know and see it and grow in the midst of it.
He must learn about activism and organization, and at the same time know the different layers of black experiences and living conditions, and what we must do to become free and free ourselves.
Even if I manage to raise her without personally experiencing blatant racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would do him a disservice if I protected him from this world.”
The first stop they made when they reached Ferguson was on South Florissant, a place across the road from the police station, which had become a kind of campground where activists were waiting for news about policeman Darren Wilson, who was ultimately not charged.
There, Ferrell and his daughter joined forces with a local business owner who prepared lunches.
They put food bags together and helped to distribute them to the protesters.
For Ferrell, a new type of activism slowly began to take shape.
"My activism changed completely after August 9," he said, noting that when he was a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, he was president of the Association of Minorities Nursing Students and focused on food justice and health inequalities in black communities.
“I didn’t have any organizational experience.
It all just went wrong.”
Weeks later, during an evening demonstration, Ferrell met with one of the film's co-directors, Sabah Folayan.
Folayan said he and filmmaker Lucas Alvarado-Farrar simply wanted to document what was going on.
Ferrell asked, “Are you trying to document what’s going on, or are you trying to find a story that can be used?”
Such skepticism was the result of countless cases where people, often white people, come into the community and try to benefit from its pain and resilience.
Folayan explained in a recent interview: “We’ve heard that the voices of people born and raised in Ferguson are not being heard and we wanted to do it differently.”
Folayan had already shaken hands with co-director Damon Davis, a regional artist known for his activism in relation to death row prisoners.
His involvement made the project appealing to Ferrell and six other locals who were watched for years by the crew of the film Whose Streets? after Brown was shot.
"In this documentary, no one is speaking for us or with us, we are speaking for ourselves," Davis said.
"It was important to me how these people were portrayed, because that's how they portray me."
While the goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experience -- to show that the movement was not "the redeemer's direction, but the gathering of the community," as Folayan said -- he became the most open participant in the film.
As a result, Whose Streets? documents surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell’s life, such as falling in love and marrying his wife.
"I felt like I was naked," Ferrell said, laughing at the first time he saw the film.
“But I realized that doing this work and humanizing black people must be accompanied by a certain vulnerability.”
What’s more, Ferrell’s story emphasizes and refocuses the role of a black homosexual woman in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three initiators of the movement who came up with the theme <0x23>BlackLivesMatter after the murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 are homosexual.
"In their leading roles, black homosexual women have sustained the movement in general," Ferrell said, " precisely because we have to constantly fight on several fronts.
Black homosexual women have to carry all this burden.”
Folayan agreed, noting that "the movement is indeed sustained by black women, and many of them are black homosexual women."
At the same time, he argues that “this isn’t some sort of a form of creating equal opportunities”—Ferrelli wasn’t chosen as the center of the film because of his identity.
"He was a person who blew the right energy," he said.
"But it's no coincidence that she was right on the front line, because living as a black homosexual woman at such junctions is a lot at stake.
You can see his energy through the screen.”
Meanwhile, news cameras have long since disappeared from Ferguson, but racial ties between the community and the police remain fragile.
Ferrell's conditional sentence for blocking the road during the protest will last for another 2.5 years.
He describes the social-political atmosphere in the region he calls home, simply as a “massive booze.”
Nevertheless, he still attaches importance to the mantra that he has etched into his memory since he went to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We need to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains.”
