The rules for handling genetically modified crops must be clear
The Ministry of Rural Affairs sent the Bill on Amendments to the Environmental Release of Genetically Modified Organisms Act (GMOVS) and the Plant Protection Act to the coordination circle.
With the amendment to the Act, the creation of a separate database for both the locations and handlers of genetically modified (GM) crops will be abandoned, for which the plant health register will be used in the future.
In addition, the obligation of a GM crop handler to have a prior agreement with a person engaged in apiculture within the prescribed radius will be amended.
Although genetically modified crops are not currently grown in Estonia, we consider it necessary to have clear rules for the coexistence of genetically modified and non-genetically modified crops.
At least until it has been decided to declare Estonia GMO-free," said Sigmar Suu, the head of the plant health department at the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
"At the same time, it must be taken into account that the measures developed must be purposeful and proportionate, taking into account the costs and administrative burden for both the private and public sectors," Suu added.
The Bill repeals the provisions related to the database of the locations and handlers of GM crops and the training in handling in the GMOVS, and establishes the requirements for the handling of GM crops and the commencement of economic activities.
In the specific case of beekeeping, the current obligation of the GM crop grower to inform beekeepers of the start of the cultivation of the GM crop is replaced by the obligation to reach an appropriate agreement with the beekeeper before the start of the cultivation.
The Bill has been sent to the ministries for approval.
All interested parties have the opportunity to consult it in the information system of the Bills and, if they wish, to submit their opinion to the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
The planned changes will primarily affect persons active in the field of plant production, beekeepers and the Agricultural Board.
In the European Union, including Estonia, only one GM crop - maize MON 810 - is allowed to be grown.
So far, however, no Estonian farmer has been interested in growing GM crops.
This is due to the fact that there is no corn pest in Estonia, the European strawberry strain, against which the maize MON 810 is resistant.
Varieties of this corn line are also bred for the southern regions, and this corn is not suitable for our climatic conditions.
In 2015 and 2016, the Ministry of Rural Affairs commissioned studies to detect possible contamination with GM organisms in the seeds of different varieties of summer oilseed rape, maize and soya grown in Estonia.
The analysis results of the samples showed that the seeds did not contain any foreign genes and the results of the study concluded that the seeds of rapeseed, maize and soya varieties grown in Estonia do not contain genetically modified organisms.
From the foregoing, it can be concluded that genetically modified crops are not consciously grown in Estonia, and it was also confirmed that there has been no accidental contamination.
