Drinking alcohol is equivalent to “training” the brain.
Livestrong writes that Dr. Gordon Sheperd is such a big wine fan that he believes wine can train the brain better than anything else in the world.
Sheperd is a neuroscientist at Yale University.
According to him, it is not about alcohol or how it affects our feelings and thoughts, but rather about the “very active” process of tasting wine.
By sniffing the glass, swirling the wine in the mouth, enjoying it, and sensing the aftertaste, we put our brains to work to create a taste for the wine.
Wine molecules don’t actually contain taste, but taste comes from the way wine stimulates the brain.
It shows how the brain “sees” colors.
"Taste is not in wine, taste is created by the taster of wine," says Sheperd.
The things that still affect the formation of the taste of wine are, for example, our age, gender, and even the amount of saliva that a person produces.
Sheperd, of course, warns us that wine isn't about getting drunk.
“There has to be more,” he says.
If you drink too much, the system is oversaturated.
Excessive wine drinking can harm the brain rather than benefit it, according to a 2004 study, people who drink more than three glasses of wine risk memory loss, imbalance, and reduced mental capacity.
